Absolutely agree — perfection is the enemy of progress. Launching with a product that’s good enough, not perfect, and iterating based on real user feedback is the key to scaling. The metrics you mentioned — user growth, engagement, revenue — are the true north stars. 

What’s often overlooked is the balance between product-market fit and product quality. Early on, you want to prioritize solving a real problem for a specific audience, even if the solution isn’t polished. Once you have traction, you can invest in refining the product. 

I’ve seen too many teams get stuck in the “perfect product” trap, delaying launch and missing their window. It’s not about shipping bugs — it’s about shipping value. And once